nety nautical miles northeast of the African shore. Ben-Yehoyada intertwines the town's recent turbulent history-which has been fraught with conflicts over fishing rights, development projects, and how the Mediterranean should figure in Italian politics at large-with deep accounts of life aboard the Naumacho, linking ethnography with historical anthropology and political-economic analysis. Through this sophisticated approach, he crafts a new viewpoint on the historical processes of transnational region formation, one offered by these moving ships as they weave together new social and political constellations.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aFisherszMediterranean Region. 4aItaly. 4aMediterranean. 4aSicily. 4aTunisia. 4ahistorical anthropology. 4apolitical economy. 4apolitical imaginary. 4aregion formation. 4ascale. 4atransnationalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226451169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780226451169.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles